AGI - The accusation of not acting for the Palestinian population > is one of the factors that have determined the collapse of the Akp> party, in power in Turkey for 20 years. Yet in recent months Turkish President Recep Tayip Erdogan> has not misled verbal attacks and charges against the Israeli government for the harsh offensive against Palestinian civilians in the Gaza Strip. Erdogan has repeatedly called Israeli prime minister Benjamin Netanyahu as a executioner of Hitler, Mussolini and Stalin, repeatedly accused the Israeli government of crimes against humanity and supported the cause for genocide brought by South Africa at the Hague International Justice Court.
&nbsp;
In addition to welcoming the sick and wounded in Gaza and sending aid more than any other country, the Turkish government has offered its willingness to act as a guarantor for the creation of a Palestinian state, hosted Hamas leaders and recalled the ambassador to Tel Aviv, appointed just a year earlier. Yet a large proportion of the Turkish population accuses Erdogan of not doing enough, > of not acting in a concrete way or of "saving the Palestinians in exchange for Israeli money". An accusation that this time does not come from parties or movements of opposition, but from the very basis of the Akp party, which Erdogan over the years forged in his own image and likeness.
&nbsp;
The criticisms ended with heavy consequences in recent administrative elections, where Akp lost not only the country's first political force, but also strongholds in which he ruled over the last two decades. Where it has been confirmed, the party of Erdogan has however recorded a consistent decline. An example in this sense is the city of Erzurum, > one of the most important centers in the north east of the country where the consent of Erdogan has always been firm. Erzurum in the last few months has been upholstered with banners against the Israeli attack, sit in solidarity and gazebo to raise aid for the people of Gaza. The Akp confirmed its control over the city, but lost 13% in 5 years>. Same thing in Sakarya, another strong > where Akp confirmed, but where the lost points were 18 compared to 2019>.
&nbsp;
In Sakarya, during the rally scheduled for the president's election tour, a banner appeared among the crowd to ask to end "of shameless trade with Israel". At the banner, then removed, Erdogan did not react, but being challenged to his own event is an unprecedented fact for the Turkish leader.&nbsp; In the administrative elections on 31 March, the growth of the Conservative Islamic party Yeniden Refah was stirred. The latter was able in 10 months to go beyond the double of the previously obtained consents and conquer three districts, including Urfa, an important province on the border with Syria for years under control of Akp.
&nbsp;
A boom of consensus to be observed in the near future, which finds its foundations precisely in the loss of consensus of the Akp and in the electoral campaign focused on the "vergogna" and the accusations of ineffectiveness in making Turkey voice against Israel heard. Of course, in order to understand the collapse of Erdogan, we must consider the economic problems of the country, the unstoppable increase in inflation, the loss of being able to purchase minimum pensions and wages, but it is undeniable that the reaction, judged 'insufficient', against Israeli operations in Gaza was a factor. To make the idea a Yeniden Refah electoral ad launched on the internet in which a vote for the Akp turned into the stamp of an Israeli flag.
&nbsp;
Factor admitted by Erdogan in front of his with a perennial "we paid the price of having failed to assert our position". To make the idea of the paradox the comment of the Israeli Foreign Minister, Israel Katz, who declared that the defeat of Erdogan is a "punishment for attacks on Israel". Erdogan is accused of not inflicting economic sanctions.> A road that Turkey actually avoids, as it happened for Russia, a choice that however this time had a price to pay. Yet, as reported by data from the Ministry of Economy and confirmed by observers not aligned with the Turkish government, from 7 October to today the trade between Turkey and Israel has collapsed by 33%.
&nbsp;
Ankara denied that government and institutions have concluded agreements with the Jewish State. Data not enough to counteract to the tam tam of social, where for example are appeared photos of a supply of 21 tons of boric acid powdered to an Israeli company, the Fertilizers &amp; Chemical Ltd, which produces chemicals. A tweet to which no one answered and that created scandal with a public opinion compactly pro-Palestinian. The business charges with the Jewish state favored a hemorrhage of heavy votes at the most conservative electorate in the east center of Anatolia. Erdogan will have to answer these allegations, try to make Turkish policy more incisive towards Gaza and put under the magnifying glass the affairs between Turkey and Israel. It is necessary to prevent the loss of consent from continuing with the conservatives and religious, until now the basis of the power of Erdogan.

